<div id="abbrev" class="read-length">
  <h2>Appendix 1<br />Abbreviations policy</h2>

  <p>Return to <a href="/information-for-transcribers/fields-in-the-freecen1-spreadsheet" title="Fields in the FreeCEN1 spreadsheet">Field descriptions</a>&#160;(or return to the <a href="/cms/information-for-transcribers/draft-information-for-using-the-csi-online-transcription-system" title="Information for using the CSI online transcription system">Online Transcription instructions</a>&#160;which supersede these instructions)</p>
  <p>While the intention is that transcription should be <q>as is</q>, there will be occasions when the full Census entry is too long (for FreeCEN1 - no such restriction applies to online transcriptions). Our aim is that the <em>average reader</em> will be able to interpret any abbreviation we may use. </p>
  <p>Use accepted forms where-ever possible as in: “Lieut” for Lieutenant, “Capt” for Captain, “JP” for Justice of the Peace, “GP” for General (Medical) Practitioner, “RN” for Royal Navy, etc.</p>
  <p>It is often safe to remove vowels: “schlr” for scholar, “mstr” for master, “mkr” for maker, “jrnymn” for journeyman, “blksmth” for blacksmith, “fshrmn” for fisherman, etc.</p>
  <p>Some occupations will stand severe abbreviation: “Farmer, 150 acres, employing 4 men, 2 women and 1 boy” is still understandable if shortened to “Farmer 150ac emp 4m 2w 1b” (only 25 characters!).</p>
  <p>Always <q>voice</q> what you have written, to ensure that it sounds something like the original entry.</p>
</div> 
