<div id="occupation">
  <h2>Appendix 4<br />Occupation abbreviations</h2>
  <div class="push--bottom"></div>
  <p>Return to <a href="/information-for-transcribers/fields-in-the-freecen1-spreadsheet" title="Fields in the FreeCEN1 spreadsheet">Field descriptions</a>&#160;(or return to the <a href="/information-for-transcribers/draft-information-for-using-the-csi-online-transcription-system" title="Information for using the CSI online transcription system">Online Transcription instructions</a>&#160;which supercede these instructions)</p>
	
  <div class="read-length">
    <p>For the <strong>1841</strong> census, enumerators were told to use the following abbreviations for common occupations. Some enumerators continued to use these abbreviations for later censuses. FreeCEN policy is to expand these abbreviations where there is no doubt about the intended meaning.</p>
    <p>In this alphabetical list, the enumerator abbreviation is followed by the occupation in full.</p>
  </div>
  <div class="grid--double">
    <div class="grid__item one-half lap-one-whole palm-one-whole">
      <dl class="data data--compact lap-flush--bottom palm-flush--bottom">
        <dt class="data__name">A. or Ap.</dt> <dd class="data__value">Apprentice — can be abbreviated as “appren”</dd>
        <dt class="data__name">Ag. Lab. or A.L.</dt> <dd class="data__value">Agricultural Labourer — can be abbreviated as “ag lab”</dd>
        <dt class="data__name">Army H.P.</dt> <dd class="data__value">Army, Half-Pay</dd>
        <dt class="data__name">Army Pen.</dt> <dd class="data__value">Army Pensioner</dd>
